#Text=Wikinews
#Text=:
#Text=There were recently reports in the Belgian media about the rise of reported internet crime .
#Text=Does that illustrate your call for international regulations of internet behaviour ?
#Text=If someone poses problematic behaviour on the internet , how should he or she be dealt with ?
#Text=Robert Cailliau
#Text=: What do we use in common law ?
#Text=The police searches for the offender and works through a number of procedures .
#Text=There are rules for establishing complicity .
#Text=On the net it is only different because time and space break down there .
#Text=Problematic behaviour , as you euphemistically call it , can be exhibited from anywhere and it usually goes very fast .
#Text=We therefore need a world-wide law .
#Text=There are however at least three large legal frameworks in conflict here : the European , the US and the Chinese systems .
#Text=Making those work together is a problem that I do not see solved in time .
#Text=What upsets me too is the idea that it is the responsibility of the ISP or service to act .
#Text=Recently MySpace removed a number of users that were known as sex offenders .
#Text=They must have used some register .
#Text=Who decided that ?
#Text=Who transmitted the register ?
#Text=The reaction of Scotland Yard was right : it 's not because these people had committed an offence that they should be excluded forever , certainly not when they had served their sentences .
#Text=Or we should first change the law .
#Text=But we see more and more cases in which commercial companies take the law in their own hands .
#Text=We see more and more cases in which commercial companies take the law in their own hands .
#Text=And that makes me worried about what the commercial sector will do in the vacuum that the governments just let be .
#Text=— Robert Cailliau
#Text=And that makes me worried about what the commercial sector will do in the vacuum that the governments just let be .
#Text=Much more than about what governments would do .
#Text=That in turn is related to my worries over leaving my data in the hands of sites rather than having full control myself .
#Text=Let 's not forget that the sex offenders maybe did nothing wrong in MySpace .
#Text=The terms of MySpace are very simple : they have the right to do what they want and to exclude you when they want without reason .
#Text=In addition they transfer all your data to the U.S. , although they are honest enough to warn you that the protection of private data in the U.S. " may be different " .
#Text=No , I prefer to stay away from social sites in these circumstances .
#Text=Finally , do these sex offenders have a telephone ?
#Text=That is allowed ?
#Text=And they can use the post office ?
#Text=And the road system with their cars ?
#Text=Yeah , let 's just keep on messing about .
